.SH NAME
Linux::Event::Operation \- In\-flight operation object for Linux::Event::Proactor
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 6
\&  my $op = $loop\->read(
\&    fh          => $fh,
\&    len         => 4096,
\&    data        => $ctx,
\&    on_complete => sub ($op, $result, $ctx) {
\&      return if $op\->is_cancelled;
\&
\&      if ($op\->failed) {
\&        warn $op\->error\->message;
\&        return;
\&      }
\&
\&      my $state = $op\->state;
\&      my $kind  = $op\->kind;
\&      my $res   = $op\->result;
\&    },
\&  );
\&
\&  $op\->cancel;
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
\&\f(CW\*(C`Linux::Event::Operation\*(C'\fR represents one in\-flight action submitted through
Linux::Event::Proactor. Users obtain operation objects from the proactor
loop; they are not normally constructed directly.
.PP
An operation carries its kind, state, result or error, optional user data, and
a deferred completion callback.
.SH STATES
.IX Header "STATES"
An operation begins in \f(CW\*(C`pending\*(C'\fR and then settles exactly once into one of
these terminal states:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`done\*(C'\fR
.Sp
The operation completed. Inspect \f(CW\*(C`success\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`failed\*(C'\fR to distinguish success
from failure.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`cancelled\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Cancellation won the race.
.SH METHODS
.IX Header "METHODS"
.SS loop
.IX Subsection "loop"
Return the owning proactor.
.SS kind
.IX Subsection "kind"
Return the operation kind, such as \f(CW\*(C`read\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`send\*(C'\fR, or \f(CW\*(C`timeout\*(C'\fR.
.SS data
.IX Subsection "data"
Return the user data payload associated with the operation.
.SS state
.IX Subsection "state"
Return the state string.
.SS result
.IX Subsection "result"
Return the normalized success result, if any.
.SS error
.IX Subsection "error"
Return the Linux::Event::Error object for failed operations.
.SS is_pending
.IX Subsection "is_pending"
.SS is_done
.IX Subsection "is_done"
.SS is_cancelled
.IX Subsection "is_cancelled"
Predicate helpers for state inspection.
.SS success
.IX Subsection "success"
True when the operation completed successfully.
.SS failed
.IX Subsection "failed"
True when the operation completed with an error.
.SS cancel
.IX Subsection "cancel"
Request cancellation through the owning proactor.
.SH CALLBACKS
.IX Header "CALLBACKS"
The user callback, if one was supplied, is queued by the proactor and later run
with this ABI:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&  $cb\->($op, $result, $data)
.Ve
.PP
Callbacks are never executed inline by the backend.
